-The '''accession of Autonomous Republic of Crimea and the city of Sevastopol to the Russian Federation''' is a disputed diplomatic process that began after the [[Autonomous Republic of Crimea]] and the city of [[Sevastopol]] unilaterally declared [[Declaration of Independence of the Republic of Crimea|their independence]] from [[Ukraine]].
+The '''accession of Republic of Crimea to the Russian Federation''' is a disputed diplomatic process that began after the [[Autonomous Republic of Crimea]] and the city of [[Sevastopol]] unilaterally declared [[Declaration of Independence of the Republic of Crimea|their independence]] from [[Ukraine]].

 The regions joined together [[Republic of Crimea (country)|as a single nation]] afterwards and requested to be [[wikt:accession|acceded]] to Russia as such, in accordance with [[Crimean referendum, 2014|a referendum that reflected such desire]]. Russia granted the request almost immediately by signing [[Treaty on the Adoption of the Republic of Crimea to Russia|an adoption treaty]] together with the newly formed nation. The accession, however, was ratified separately: [[Republic of Crimea|one for the Autonomous Republic]] as [[federal subjects of Russia|a federal subject]] and another for Sevastopol as [[federal cities of Russia|a federal city]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.itar-tass.com/russia/724785|title=Putin signs laws on reunification of Republic of Crimea and Sevastopol with Russia|publisher=[[ITAR TASS]]|date=21 March 2014 |accessdate=March 21, 2014}}</ref> Ukraine, however, disputes the treaty as it does not consider the independence of the Autonomous Republic and Sevastopol as legitimate, nor the accession itself. So does the majority of the international community who has condemned Russia's actions.{{citationneeded|date=March 2014}}

